SIMPLE: preventive
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Preventive
<hw>Pre*vent"ive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧ventif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Going before;
preceding.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Any previous counsel or <qex>preventive</qex> understanding.</q>
<rj><qau>Cudworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tending to defeat or hinder; obviating; preventing
the access of; <as>as, a medicine <ex>preventive</ex> of
disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Physic is either curative or <qex>preventive</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Preventive service</b></col>, <cd>the duty performed by
the armed police in guarding the coast against smuggling.</cd>
<mark>[Eng]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preventive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Preventive
<hw>Pre*vent"ive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which prevents, hinders,
or obstructs; that which intercepts access; in medicine, something to
prevent disease; a prophylactic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preventively</ent>⟦br⟧
